# The seven file types

The **first character** of every `ls -l` line is the type.

```
-rw-r--r--   d rwxr-xr-x   lrwxrwxrwx
↑            ↑             ↑
type         directory     symlink
```

## The seven

| | | |
|---|---|---|
| **`-`** | regular file | text, binaries, images — most files |
| **`d`** | directory | holds `name → inode` entries |
| **`l`** | symbolic link | a pointer to another path |
| **`c`** | char device | byte stream — terminals, `/dev/null` |
| **`b`** | block device | disks — `/dev/sda`, `/dev/nvme0n1` |
| **`s`** | socket | local service endpoint — `/run/docker.sock` |
| **`p`** | named pipe | a persistent pipe on disk |

You live in the **first three**. Devices in `/dev` are how userspace reaches hardware; sockets are how local daemons talk.

⚠️ Not the same as **`file`** — `file` reads a *regular file's contents*; the `ls -l` char is the **type the kernel sees**.
